Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Baffie","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: variant of   Boffin  , itself a variant of   Boughen  , with unrounding of [o] to [a]."],"variants":[{"name":"Boughen","meanings":["(2010: NA)","Welsh and English (Norfolk): probably also a variant of   Baughan  , which is itself the base-form from which   Vaughan   originates.","English (Norfolk): apparently a variant of <b>Bowgen</b>, a nickname from Old French <i>bouzon</i>, <i>bougon</i> ‘large arrow, crossbow bolt (as a heraldic device)’, perhaps used metaphorically of a person who bore some physical resemblance to a bolt. Compare   Busson   1."]},{"name":"Boffin","meanings":["English: unexplained, probably a variant of   Boughen  ."]}]},{"name":"Béatrix","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Late Latin personal name, which was borne by a saint martyred in Rome, together with Saints Faustinus and Simplicius, in the early 4th century. The original form of the name was probably <i>Viatrix</i>, a feminine version of <i>Viator</i> ‘voyager (through life)’, which was a favourite name among early Christians. This was then altered by association with Latin <i>Beatus</i> ‘blessed’ (<i>Via-</i> and <i>Bea-</i> sometimes being pronounced the same in Late Latin).  See also  Beatrice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Béatrix de Baffie was born about 1210. She married Agne V d'Olliergues in 1235, in Olliergues, Puy-de-Dôme, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died about 1279, at the age of 71."},"et":{"environ 1210–environ 1279":"umbes 1210–umbes 1279","1180–1252":"1180–1252","1230–1272":"1